The paper proposes a supervised learning algorithm for spiking neural networks (SNNs) with the aim of achieving energy-efficient VLSI processor design. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of analog resistive memory, which falls under the Emerging Technologies (cs.ET) sub-category. The proposed algorithm is also evaluated on a recognition task, indicating that the paper may also belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) and/or the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AR) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the robustness of the proposed SNNs against variations in the manufacturing process, which suggests that it may also belong to the Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
